{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01U7C8oSmDZVymwXu77zK7XW","type":"tool_result","content":"<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<server description=\"Roster Jakarta EE Application\">\n\n    <!-- Enable Jakarta EE features -->\n    <featureManager>\n        <feature>jakartaee-10.0</feature>\n    </featureManager>\n\n    <!-- HTTP endpoint -->\n    <httpEndpoint id=\"defaultHttpEndpoint\"\n                  httpPort=\"8080\"\n                  httpsPort=\"9443\"\n                  host=\"*\" />\n\n    <!-- Application configuration -->\n    <webApplication id=\"roster\" location=\"roster.war\" contextRoot=\"/\">\n        <classloader apiTypeVisibility=\"+third-party\" />\n    </webApplication>\n\n    <!-- H2 DataSource configuration using application-bundled H2 driver -->\n    <library id=\"h2Lib\">\n        <fileset dir=\"${server.config.dir}/lib\" includes=\"h2-*.jar\"/>\n    </library>\n\n    <dataSource id=\"RosterDS\" jndiName=\"jdbc/RosterDS\">\n        <jdbcDriver libraryRef=\"h2Lib\"/>\n        <properties.generic\n            URL=\"jdbc:h2:mem:roster;DB_CLOSE_DELAY=-1;DB_CLOSE_ON_EXIT=FALSE\"\n            user=\"sa\"\n            password=\"\"/>\n    </dataSource>\n\n</server>","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"98f0c157-25c8-4522-ad5d-c073f4a9b639","uuid":"967f5828-b825-46db-8d7f-59abe2b13ca6"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_019ARErXA94WDFY8x7BdFdWV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Wait - the deployed server.xml is DIFFERENT from what I wrote. The `liberty:deploy` generated its own. Also I notice the `jndiName` is `jdbc/RosterDS` (capital R) vs my `persistence.xml` which uses `jdbc/rosterDS` (lowercase r). Also there's a `DefaultDataSource` error in the logs. Let me look more carefully - there's also no `classloader commonLibraryRef` on the web application.\n\nThe issue is that the `liberty:deploy` goal overrides server.xml. Let me fix this by:\n1. Fixing the server.xml to match what liberty generates\n2. Making sure the persistence.xml references the correct JNDI name\n3. Or... use a different approach - configure things in a way that Liberty can resolve H2\n\nActually, wait - the Liberty Maven Plugin has already generated a decent server.xml. The problem is just:\n1. The H2 classpath is empty (`Searched in: []`) - the `fileset` dir might not have the jar, or\n2. There's a `DefaultDataSource` reference that's separate from `RosterDS`\n\nLet me look at the actual liberty target directory to understand what liberty:deploy did:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":665,"cache_read_input_tokens":104493,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":665,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":460},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"98f0c157-25c8-4522-ad5d-c073f4a9b639","uuid":"0dcb39db-dcf5-4098-b490-ba16736e8669"}
